  "method": "Freeze-and-Residual with Anchor Distillation (FRAD)\n\n1) Freeze the base, add small residuals, and snapshot a teacher. Copy the current model M0 as a frozen teacher and keep it for reference. In the student, freeze all base weights and insert lightweight residual adaptation modules R (e.g., LoRA/adapters after feed‑forward blocks and a TaskRes-style residual on the task head). Zero‑initialize R so behavior initially matches M0. Add a simple gate g(x) that can bypass R at inference for inputs that look like prior domains (estimated by a domain discriminator or teacher–student agreement score).\n\n2) Build a data‑free “anchor” distribution that approximates prior knowledge without storing old data. For language models, sample prompts from public corpora and from M0 itself (nucleus/top‑k) to form unlabeled anchors; for vision or other modalities, use broad unlabeled web data or synthesize pseudo‑inputs via feature inversion so their intermediate activations match stored teacher statistics. Instead of retaining raw historical data, maintain a tiny summary memory per layer: a set of activation centroids and low‑rank bases (from online PCA over teacher features on anchors). Optionally keep a few synthetic pseudo‑exemplars generated to match these centroids; discard any real prior examples.\n\n3) Train with alternating preservation and acquisition steps, updating only R (and optionally layer norms). On new task batches Dnew, optimize the standard task loss Lnew (e.g., cross‑entropy or next‑token loss). On anchor batches A, preserve prior behavior via multi‑level distillation: minimize KL(pM0(y|x) || pM(y|x)) at the output and match intermediate features to the stored centroids/bases (e.g., L2 on projected activations). Add a small L2/orthogonality penalty that keeps R low‑norm and discourages changes along directions of high teacher sensitivity. Alternate A and Dnew mini‑batches (or mix with a tunable ratio ρ), using temperature‑scaled KL on anchors to stabilize training.\n\n4) Route at inference and adapt online. Use g(x) to disable residuals on inputs likely from old domains (ensuring exact preservation) and enable R on new‑domain inputs. In streaming settings, refine R from an error buffer built from mispredicted queries, while sampling anchors in parallel to maintain stability. Follow a mixture schedule that ensures diversity across in‑distribution and OOD clusters when drawing anchors and updates, and track retention and adaptation with a small held‑out probe of anchors synthesized on the fly (no private data retained).",
  "rationale": "Freezing the base model stops destructive overwrites that cause catastrophic forgetting; confining changes to small residual modules learns new behaviors additively. Anchoring the student to a frozen teacher through KL and feature‑level distillation on unlabeled/synthetic inputs preserves prior functions without needing to store original training data. Alternating optimization over new‑task and anchor batches stabilizes learning under distribution shift, while a lightweight inference gate ensures backward compatibility by bypassing residuals on legacy inputs.\n\nThe summary memory (centroids/PCA) and pseudo‑exemplars capture sufficient statistics of prior representations, enabling data‑free preservation. In streaming deployments, drawing updates from error streams and balanced anchor sampling maintains performance under non‑stationarity while providing clear retention/adaptation metrics.",
