  "method": "We propose Uncertainty-Guided Parameter-Isolated Adaptation (UPIA), a rehearsal-light continual learning recipe that updates a model with new data while preserving prior skills. The backbone is kept stable and augmented with a bank of lightweight, task-specific modules (adapters/LoRA for weights or prefix/visual prompts for inputs). A small routing head operates in the pre-logit latent space to choose which module(s) to engage per input. For each new task, we instantiate a fresh module and train it on the new data while freezing the backbone and previously learned modules.\n\nTraining a new module proceeds with two coupled objectives: task learning and functional preservation. Task learning optimizes the new head and its adapter/prompt using uncertainty-weighted gradients: examples and parameters with higher predictive or estimation uncertainty receive stronger updates, while confident regions are updated conservatively. Functional preservation uses self-distillation from a frozen reference model (backbone plus previously learned router/modules) evaluated on the same new-task inputs—no past data are stored. We match both logits and intermediate features so that representations used by old tasks remain stable where the new data overlaps them, and we regularize the backbone via a small, diagonal importance map accumulated online to prevent drift on parameters identified as critical for past tasks.\n\nTo route inputs and to decide when and how strongly to update, we attach a discriminative latent head with a set of trainable prototypes per task. At inference, cosine similarities to task prototypes drive a soft routing distribution over modules; a deterministic confidence score flags out-of-domain inputs, in which case the router backs off to the shared backbone or a mixture of experts. During training on a new task, the same prototypes provide a fast uncertainty signal to upweight difficult cases and to trigger expansion (adding a new module) rather than overwriting shared features when the model is uncertain.\n\nPeriodically, we compact and consolidate. Using the online importance map and cosine alignment between adapter-induced updates and backbone gradients, we selectively merge low-interference subspaces of mature adapters back into the backbone via low-rank fusion, then prune seldom-used modules. We retain only tiny, non-data artifacts per past task: the diagonal importance map and a handful of latent prototypes for routing/distillation—no raw examples. To further stabilize under distribution shift without rehearsal, we add a lightweight feature-alignment head (adversarial discriminator on shared features) so the new module learns domain-invariant representations compatible with the frozen teacher.\n\nThis end-to-end procedure yields bounded memory growth (small adapters/prompts + prototypes + importance stats), rehearsal-free preservation via on-the-fly self-distillation on current inputs, and adaptive optimization that concentrates change where the model is uncertain while shielding parameters deemed important for prior skills.",
  "rationale": "Catastrophic forgetting is driven by interference: updating parameters critical to old tasks to fit new data. UPIA reduces interference structurally by isolating most task-specific change to small adapters/prompts and by routing inputs to the right module, and functionally by distilling the frozen model’s behavior on current inputs so the shared representation and outputs do not drift in regions overlapping prior capabilities. Because distillation uses only the new data stream, no past examples are retained.\n\nUncertainty plays two roles: it gates update strength so that confident, well-established behavior is preserved, and it triggers expansion (new modules) only when needed, preventing destructive overwriting. The online importance map further protects parameters most responsible for prior tasks during any consolidation. Together, parameter isolation, rehearsal-free self-distillation, uncertainty-guided optimization, and selective consolidation provide a practical path to learn from new data without catastrophic forgetting and without storing all prior data.\n\nMemory remains small and bounded: only lightweight modules, a diagonal importance vector, and a few latent prototypes per task are kept. Optional adversarial feature alignment improves cross-domain compatibility, further reducing reliance on replay while maintaining performance on past skills.",
